6.9'''<ref name=\"phare\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.nsi.bg/ORPDOCS/Census2011_1.pop_by_age.xls]</ref>||align=\"center\"|'''65.2'''|| || \n|}\n\n==Population==\n\nThe Pazardzhik province had a [[population]] of 310,741 (310,723 also given) according to a 2001 [[census]], of which {{pct|153043|310741|1}} were [[male]] and {{pct|157680|310741|1}} were [[female]].<ref name=\"NSI Census 2001\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/PopObl.htm Population to 01.03.2001 by Area and Sex] from [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/nav.htm Bulgarian ''National Statistical Institute'': Census 2001]</ref>\nAs of the end of 2009, the population of the province, announced by the Bulgarian National Statistical Institute, numbered 290,614<ref name=\"divisions\"/> of which {{pct|66111|290614|1}} are inhabitants aged over 60 years.<ref name=\"NSI age\">{{in lang|en}} [http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1587#cont Bulgarian National Statistical Institute - Population by age in 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513121908/http://www.nsi.bg/otrasalen.php?otr=53&a1=1583&a2=1584&a3=1587 |date=2012-05-13 }}</ref>\n\nTotal population (2011 census): 275 548<ref name=\"nsi.bg\"/>\n\n<!--THIS TABLE IS STANDARD TO ALL BULGARIAN PROVINCE'S ARTICLES. PLEASE LEAVE -->\nThe following table represents the change of the population in the province after [[World War II]]:\n{{Table BG Province population\n| province = Pazardzhik\n| 1946 = 247,014\n| 1956 = 278,777\n| 1965 = 296,641\n| 1975 = 314,006\n| 1985 = 325,971\n| 1992 = 326,123\n| 2001 = 310,741\n| 2005 = 297,781\n| 2007 = 294,086\n| 2009 = 290,614\n| 2011 = 275,548\n| ref 1 = <ref name=\"divisions\"/>\n| ref 2 = <ref name=\"population\"/>\n| ref 3 = <ref name=\"pop-stat-divisions\"/>\n}}\n\n===Ethnic groups===\n{{bar box\n| title=Ethnic groups in Pazardzhik Province (2011 census)\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| left1=Ethnic group\n| right1=Percentage\n| float=right\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Bulgarians in Bulgaria|Bulgarians]]|#00966E|83.8}}\n{{bar percent|[[Romani people in Bulgaria|Romani]]|brown|8.3}}\n{{bar percent|[[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]]|red|5.7}}\n{{bar percent|others and indefinable|purple|2.2}}\n}}\nTotal population (2011 census): 275 548<br>\nEthnic groups (2011 census):<ref>[http://www.nsi.bg/ORPDOCS/Census2011_4.pop_by_ethnos.xls Population by province, municipality, settlement and ethnic identification, by 01.02.2011; Bulgarian National Statistical Institute] {{in lang|bg}}</ref>\nIdentified themselves: 246,002 persons:\n*[[Bulgarians in Bulgaria|Bulgarians]]:  206 110 (83,78%)\n*[[Romani people in Bulgaria|Romani]]: 20 350 (8,27%)\n*[[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]]: 14 062 (5,72%)\n*Others and indefinable: 5 480 (2,23%)\nA further 30,000 persons in Pazardzhik Province did not declare their ethnic group at the 2011 census.\n\nEthnic groups in the province according to 2001 census:<ref name=\"NSI Census 2001 Ethnicity\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/Ethnos.htm Population to 01.03.2001 by District and Ethnic Group] from [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/nav.htm Bulgarian ''National Statistical Institute'': Census 2001]</ref>\n261,260 [[Bulgarians in Bulgaria|Bulgarians]] ({{pct|261260|310723|1}}),<br> 23,970 [[Romani people in Bulgaria|Romani]] ({{pct|23970|310723|1}}),\n20,448 [[Turks in Bulgaria|Turks]] ({{pct|20448|310723|1}} )and 5045 others and unspecified ({{pct|5045|310723|1}}).\n\n===Languages===\n\nMother tongues in the province according to 2001 census:<ref name=\"NSI Census 2001 Language\">{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/Census.htm Population to 01.03.2001 by District and Mother Tongue] from [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/nav.htm Bulgarian ''National Statistical Institute'': Census 2001]</ref>\n260,817 [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] ({{pct|260817|310723|1}}),<br> 24,204 [[Romani language|Romani]] ({{pct|24204|310723|1}}),\n21,902 [[Turkish language|Turkish]] ({{pct|21902|310723|1}}) and 3800 others and unspecified ({{pct|3800|310723|1}}).\n\n=== Religion ===\n{{bar box\n| title=Religions in Pazardzhik Province (2011 census)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pop-stat.mashke.org/bulgaria-religion2011.htm|title=\"Religious composition: 2011 census\"|publisher=pop-stat.mashke.org|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n| titlebar=#ddd\n| left1=Religious group\n| right1=Percentage\n| float=right\n| bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christian]]|#D4AF37|58.48}}\n{{bar percent|[[Islam in Bulgaria|Muslim]]|black|8.83}}\n{{bar percent|[[Protestantism in Bulgaria|Protestant Christian]]|orange|1.15}}\n{{bar percent|[[Roman Catholicism in Bulgaria|Roman Catholic Christian]]|blue|0.3}}\n{{bar percent|others and indefinable|purple|31.2}}\n}}\nReligious adherence in the province according to 2001 census:<ref>{{in lang|bg}} [http://www.nsi.bg/Census/Religion.htm Religious adherence in Bulgaria - census 2001]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=3| <small>Census 2001</small>\n|-\n! <small>religious adherence</small>  \n! <small>population</small>\n! %\n|-\n| [[Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christians]]\n| align=\"middle\" | 250,556 \t \t  \t    \n| align=\"middle\" |80.64%\t \t \n|-\n| [[Muslim]]s\n| align=\"middle\" | 46,338\n| align=\"middle\" |14.91%\n|-\n| [[Protestantism|Protestants]]\n| align=\"middle\" | 2,913\t\n| align=\"middle\" |0.94%\n|-\n| [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholics]]\n| align=\"middle\" | 260\n| align=\"middle\" |0.08%\n\n|-\n| Other\n| align=\"middle\" | 1,142 \t\n| align=\"middle\" |0.37%\n|-\n| Religion not mentioned\n| align=\"middle\" | 9,514 \t\n| align=\"middle\" |3.06%\n|-\n| '''total'''\n| align=\"middle\" | '''310,723'''\t\n| align=\"middle\" |'''100%'''\n|}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Dam-Shiroka-Poliana.jpg|thumb|left|[[Shiroka Polyana]] Reservoir.]]\nThe backbone of the economy in the region is industry. The \"Batashki Vodnosilov Pat\" is an important hydrocomplex consisting of three hydro power plants- \"Batak\", \"Peshtera\" and \"Aleko\" with combined capacity of around 250 MW. Copper extracting industry is of national and European importance with major mines located around Panagyurishte (Asarel and Medet), [[Elshitsa]], [[Tsar Asen]] and [[Mina Radka]]. Machine building industry is developed in [[Pazardzhik]] (lead acid batteries), [[Panagyurishte]] (optical), [[Velingrad]]. There is flourishing pharmaceutical industry in [[Peshtera]] with more than 1 000 employees in the plant. Paper industry is developed in [[Belovo, Bulgaria|Belovo]]. Timber industry is very important in the southern part of the region (the Rhodopes)- [[Batak, Bulgaria|Batak]], [[Peshtera]], [[Rakitovo]] and [[Velingrad]]. The manufacturing of textiles is well developed in [[Pazardzhik]], [[Panagyurishte]] and [[Velingrad]]. There is a huge footwear plant in [[Peshtera]]. Food processing industry is developed in most of the towns.\nAgriculture is also important, especially in the fertile central parts of the region. The most important crops are orchards (apples, plums and strawberries), grapes, wheat, barley, rye and rice.  Livestock breeding is relatively well developed in the mountainous areas.\n\n===Tourism===\n[[File:BatakChurch.JPG|thumb|left|A church in [[Batak, Bulgaria|Batak]].]]\nThe province has considerable opportunities to develop mountain and rural tourism, especially in the southern parts where the [[Rhodope Mountains|Rhodope]] mountains are located. The slopes are covered with dense deciduous and higher up, coniferous forests, dotted with numerous artificial lakes. The largest one is the [[Batak Dam]], on whose shores are built two resorts: ''Tsigov Chark'' and ''Saint Konstantin'' as well as many villas and shrines.  Fish is abundant in the dams, including [[carp]], [[rudd]], [[Rutilus|roach]] [[Barbel (fish)|barbel]], [[perch]], [[zander]] and many others; the mountain streams are rich in [[trout]].  There are spa resorts in [[Velingrad]], [[Strelcha]], [[Banya, Pazardzhik Province|Banya]], [[Varvara, Pazardzhik Province|Varvara]].  The most famous landmarks are located in [[Panagyurishte]], [[Pazardzhik]], [[Batak, Bulgaria|Batak]], [[Velingrad]].\n\nImpressive ruins of an ancient basilica (the [[Belovo Basilica]]) rise in the hilly country, close to the town of [[Belovo, Bulgaria|Belovo]]. Numerous ruined fortresses are scattered around the province, the most famous of these are [[Tsepina]], and the ramparts near [[Bata, Pazardzhik Province|Bata]] and [[Strelcha]]. The medieval [[Church of St Demetrius, Patalenitsa|Church of St Demetrius]] in the village of [[Patalenitsa]] has frescoes dating to the 12th\u201313th century.\n\n==Transportation and communications==\nThe road network is not dense.  The [[Trakiya motorway]] runs through the middle of the region. The main railway between [[Sofia]] and [[Plovdiv]] also runs through it.  There are two other railways: to [[Panagyurishte]] and to [[Peshtera]].  There are several military airports. \nAs everywhere in [[Bulgaria]], every town and village in the region is provided with electricity, drinking water and telephone network.  Each town and some villages are provided with Internet connection, and the cellular phone coverage is almost 100%, as most people own GSMs.\nSome of the interconnecting roads, especially higher up the mountain, are currently in a very bad state following heavy downpours in 2005 and 2006.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Provinces of Bulgaria]]\n*[[List of villages in Pazardzhik Province]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.pz.government.bg/news.php Official site of the Pazardzhik Province]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Pazardzhik Province\n|North     = [[Sofia Province]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Plovdiv Province]]\n|Southeast = [[Smolyan Province]]\n|South     = \n|Southwest = [[Blagoevgrad Province]]\n|West      = \n|Northwest = [[Sofia Province]]\n}}\n\n<br/>{{Provinces of Bulgaria}}\n{{Bulgaria topics}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:Pazardzhik Province| ]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Bulgaria]]\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePopulation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pazardzhik_Province"}
{"title_page": "Lisa Baldez", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lisa Baldez\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Princeton University]]|[[University of San Diego]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Rochester Institute of Technology]]|[[University of Rochester]]|[[Washington University in Saint Louis]]|[[Harvard University]]|[[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|[[Victoria Schuck|Victoria Schuck Award]], [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]}}\n}}\n'''Lisa Baldez''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[Latin American Studies]]. She is a Professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at [[Dartmouth College]], where she was also Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College from 2015 until 2018. She studies the relationship between [[Political system|political institutions]] and [[gender equality]], and has written about the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]], women's protests in [[Chile]], [[Women_in_government#Quotas|gender quota]] laws, and the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].\n\n==Education and early work==\nBaldez attended [[Princeton University]], where she earned a BA in Latin American Studies in 1986.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://faculty-directory.dartmouth.edu/lisa-baldez |title=Lisa Baldez |publisher=Dartmouth College |date=October 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She then completed an MA in political science at the [[University of San Diego]] in 1992, followed by a political science PhD there in 1997. Her dissertation received an Honorable Mention for the 1998 Best Dissertation Prize from the Women and Politics Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn Spring of 1997, Baldez worked as an Adjunct Professor at The [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] and The [[University of Rochester]], and in 1997 she joined the political science faculty at [[Washington University in Saint Louis]].<ref name=profile/> From 1999 to 2002, Baldez was a Harbison Faculty Fellow at Washington University in Saint Louis.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wp.las.iastate.edu/cattcenter/2009/10/13/catt-prize-winners/ |title=Carrie Chapman Catt Prize for Research on Women and Politics |publisher=Iowa State University |year=2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In Spring 2003, she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=profile/> In 2003, she became a professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at Dartmouth College.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2002, Baldez published the book ''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'', in which she studies why women protest, and in what situations they make their gender identity salient as part of their protests.<ref name=noonan>{{cite journal |first=Rita K. |last=Noonan |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=231\u2013232 |date=1 March 2004 |doi=10.1177/009430610403300260}}</ref> Baldez focuses on the struggle for [[women's suffrage]] in Chile,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Victor P. |last=Unda |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Rocky Mountain Review of Language and Literature |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013114 |date=1 January 2005 |doi=}}</ref> and on two major episodes of protests by women in Chile during the 1970s and 1980s: the protests against [[Salvador Allende]] and against [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Patricia |last=Tomic |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Canadian Journal of Latin American and Caribbean Studies / Revue canadienne des \u00e9tudes latino-am\u00e9ricaines et cara\u00efbes |volume=28 |issue=55/56 |pages=305\u2013307 |year=2003}}</ref> In both of these cases women's political mobilization was a major factor in undermining the legitimacy of a regime, even though these movements were in many ways ideologically opposite.<ref name=noonan/> Baldez theorizes that women form major social movements when partisan realignment gives them the opportunity to do so, and they are able to frame their exclusion from public life as a reason to protest apart from partisan differences,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elisabeth Jay |last=Friedman |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Political Science Quarterly |volume=118 |issue=3 |pages=531\u2013532 |date=1 October 2003}}</ref> and she tests this idea using [[archive|archival material]] and [[Interview (research)|research interviews]] with activists who were involved in the two movements.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Liesl |last=Haas |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=799\u2013800 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\nBaldez published a second book, ''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'', in 2014. In ''Defying Convention'', Baldez studies why the United States was one of very few countries that had not ratified the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which pledges to put an end to war and establishes gender equality.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jocelyn |last=Olcott |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of American Studies |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=1295\u20131297 |date=November 2017 |doi=10.1017/S0021875817001098}}</ref> Baldez examines this decision in the context of the historical development of a global norm of women's rights, and attributes American non-ratification partly to division among women's groups domestically on how best to achieve gender equality, and partly to United States obstructionism at the UN towards any initiatives by the [[Soviet Union]] and its allies.<ref name=davis>{{cite journal |first=Martha |last=Davis |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of Human Rights |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=571\u2013573 |date=1 October 2016 |doi=10.1080/14754835.2016.1165089}}</ref> She also studies how the interpretation of the text of the treaty evolved in the years after its drafting, so that the effective meaning of ratifying the treaty might be understood to have changed over time, which complicates the study of why the United States did not ratify the text in different periods.<ref name=davis/> Baldez structures her discussion using historical [[process tracing]], and compares the possibility of America ratifying the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women to its ratification of the [[International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination]] nearly 30 years after that convention's initial drafting.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Lana |last=Obradovic |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=International Feminist Journal of Politics |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=515\u2013517 |date=3 July 2015 |doi=10.1080/14616742.2015.1055140}}</ref> ''Defying Convention'' won the 2015 Victoria Schuck Award from the American Political Science Association, which is given each year for \"the best book published on women and politics\" in the previous year.<ref name=schuck>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> It also won the 2015 Best Book Award from the Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=besthr>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/section-36-best-book-award |title=Best Book Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her articles in peer-reviewed academic journals and her chapters in edited books, Baldez was also an editor of the 2008 volume ''Political Women and American Democracy: Critical Perspectives on Women and Politics Research'', together with [[Christina Wolbrecht]] and Karen Beckwith.<ref name=profile/>\n\nBaldez's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/18/11692402/parliaments-better-presidents-liberal |title=Justin Trudeau isn't magic, liberals. Parliaments make it easier to pass laws. |date=18 May 2016 |work=Vox |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[KQED-FM]], <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11743996/the-equal-rights-amendment-what-you-need-to-know |title=The Equal Rights Amendment: What You Need to Know |date=30 April 2019 |work=KQED |last=Leitsinger |first=Miranda |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-01-24/trump-impeachment-house-democrats-flatter-republican-senators-k5s5mzni |title=Democrats Try Flattery as Impeachment-Trial Tactic |date=24 January 2020 |work=Bloomberg |last=Bernstein |first=Jonathan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'' (2002)\n*\"Elected Bodies: The Gender Quota Law for Legislative Candidates in Mexico\", ''Legislative Studies Quarterly'' (2011)\n*''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'' (2014)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (2015)\n*Best Book Award, Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldez, Lisa}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Rochester faculty]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lisa Baldez\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Princeton University]]|[[University of San Diego]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Rochester Institute of Technology]]|[[University of Rochester]]|[[Washington University in Saint Louis]]|[[Harvard University]]|[[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|[[Victoria Schuck|Victoria Schuck Award]], [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]}}\n}}\n'''Lisa Baldez''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[Latin American Studies]]. She studies the relationship between [[Political system|political institutions]] and [[gender equality]], and has written about the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]], women's protests in [[Chile]], [[Women_in_government#Quotas|gender quota]] laws, and the [[Equal Rights Amendment]]. From 2015 to 2018, she was Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College.\n\n==Education and early work==\nBaldez attended [[Princeton University]], where she earned a BA in Latin American Studies in 1986.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://faculty-directory.dartmouth.edu/lisa-baldez |title=Lisa Baldez |publisher=Dartmouth College |date=October 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She then completed an MA in political science at the [[University of San Diego]] in 1992, followed by a political science PhD there in 1997. Her dissertation received an Honorable Mention for the 1998 Best Dissertation Prize from the Women and Politics Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn Spring of 1997, Baldez worked as an Adjunct Professor at The [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] and The [[University of Rochester]], and in 1997 she joined the political science faculty at [[Washington University in Saint Louis]].<ref name=profile/> From 1999 to 2002, Baldez was a Harbison Faculty Fellow at Washington University in Saint Louis.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wp.las.iastate.edu/cattcenter/2009/10/13/catt-prize-winners/ |title=Carrie Chapman Catt Prize for Research on Women and Politics |publisher=Iowa State University |year=2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In Spring 2003, she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=profile/> In 2003, she became a professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at Dartmouth College.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2002, Baldez published the book ''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'', in which she studies why women protest, and in what situations they make their gender identity salient as part of their protests.<ref name=noonan>{{cite journal |first=Rita K. |last=Noonan |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=231\u2013232 |date=1 March 2004 |doi=10.1177/009430610403300260}}</ref> Baldez focuses on the struggle for [[women's suffrage]] in Chile,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Victor P. |last=Unda |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Rocky Mountain Review of Language and Literature |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013114 |date=1 January 2005 |doi=}}</ref> and on two major episodes of protests by women in Chile during the 1970s and 1980s: the protests against [[Salvador Allende]] and against [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Patricia |last=Tomic |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Canadian Journal of Latin American and Caribbean Studies / Revue canadienne des \u00e9tudes latino-am\u00e9ricaines et cara\u00efbes |volume=28 |issue=55/56 |pages=305\u2013307 |year=2003}}</ref> In both of these cases women's political mobilization was a major factor in undermining the legitimacy of a regime, even though these movements were in many ways ideologically opposite.<ref name=noonan/> Baldez theorizes that women form major social movements when partisan realignment gives them the opportunity to do so, and they are able to frame their exclusion from public life as a reason to protest apart from partisan differences,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elisabeth Jay |last=Friedman |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Political Science Quarterly |volume=118 |issue=3 |pages=531\u2013532 |date=1 October 2003}}</ref> and she tests this idea using [[archive|archival material]] and [[Interview (research)|research interviews]] with activists who were involved in the two movements.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Liesl |last=Haas |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=799\u2013800 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\nBaldez published a second book, ''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'', in 2014. In ''Defying Convention'', Baldez studies why the United States was one of very few countries that had not ratified the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which pledges to put an end to war and establishes gender equality.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jocelyn |last=Olcott |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of American Studies |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=1295\u20131297 |date=November 2017 |doi=10.1017/S0021875817001098}}</ref> Baldez examines this decision in the context of the historical development of a global norm of women's rights, and attributes American non-ratification partly to division among women's groups domestically on how best to achieve gender equality, and partly to United States obstructionism at the UN towards any initiatives by the [[Soviet Union]] and its allies.<ref name=davis>{{cite journal |first=Martha |last=Davis |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of Human Rights |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=571\u2013573 |date=1 October 2016 |doi=10.1080/14754835.2016.1165089}}</ref> She also studies how the interpretation of the text of the treaty evolved in the years after its drafting, so that the effective meaning of ratifying the treaty might be understood to have changed over time, which complicates the study of why the United States did not ratify the text in different periods.<ref name=davis/> Baldez structures her discussion using historical [[process tracing]], and compares the possibility of America ratifying the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women to its ratification of the [[International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination]] nearly 30 years after that convention's initial drafting.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Lana |last=Obradovic |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=International Feminist Journal of Politics |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=515\u2013517 |date=3 July 2015 |doi=10.1080/14616742.2015.1055140}}</ref> ''Defying Convention'' won the 2015 Victoria Schuck Award from the American Political Science Association, which is given each year for \"the best book published on women and politics\" in the previous year.<ref name=schuck>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> It also won the 2015 Best Book Award from the Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=besthr>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/section-36-best-book-award |title=Best Book Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her articles in peer-reviewed academic journals and her chapters in edited books, Baldez was also an editor of the 2008 volume ''Political Women and American Democracy: Critical Perspectives on Women and Politics Research'', together with [[Christina Wolbrecht]] and Karen Beckwith.<ref name=profile/>\n\nBaldez's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/18/11692402/parliaments-better-presidents-liberal |title=Justin Trudeau isn't magic, liberals. Parliaments make it easier to pass laws. |date=18 May 2016 |work=Vox |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[KQED-FM]], <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11743996/the-equal-rights-amendment-what-you-need-to-know |title=The Equal Rights Amendment: What You Need to Know |date=30 April 2019 |work=KQED |last=Leitsinger |first=Miranda |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-01-24/trump-impeachment-house-democrats-flatter-republican-senators-k5s5mzni |title=Democrats Try Flattery as Impeachment-Trial Tactic |date=24 January 2020 |work=Bloomberg |last=Bernstein |first=Jonathan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'' (2002)\n*\"Elected Bodies: The Gender Quota Law for Legislative Candidates in Mexico\", ''Legislative Studies Quarterly'' (2011)\n*''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'' (2014)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (2015)\n*Best Book Award, Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldez, Lisa}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Rochester faculty]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Specific current job title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisa_Baldez"}
